  We show that, for any pair of knapsack problems, there is a single problem whose optimal solution corresponds to each problem of the pair, for two adjacent right-hand sides. [1] D.A. Babayev, F. Glover Aggregation of nonnegative integer-valued equations Discrete Appl. Math., 8 (1984), pp. 125–130 [2] D.A. Babayev, S.S. Mardanov Sequential and simultaneous aggregation of diophantine equations Discrete Appl. Math., 50 (1994), pp. 209–220 [3] C. Blair Sensitivity analysis for knapsack problems: a negative result Working Paper 96-131University of Illinois Bureau of Economics and Business Research (September 1996) [4] G.H. Bradley Transformation of integer programs to knapsack problems Discrete Math., 1 (1971), pp. 29–45 [5] A. Elimam, S. Elmaghraby On the reduction method for integer programs Discrete Appl. Math., 12 (1985), pp. 241–260 [6] M.R. Garey, D.S. Johnson Computers and Intractability W.H. Freeman and Company, San Francisco (1979) [7] F. Glover New results on equivalent integer programming formulations Math. Programming, 8 (1975), pp. 84–90 [8] F. Glover, D.A. Babayev New results for aggregating integer-valued equations Ann. Oper. Res., 58 (1995), pp. 227–242 [9] H. Greenberg A new reduction method in integer programming Discrete Appl. Math., 21 (1988), pp. 169–172 [10] M.W. Padberg Equivalent knapsack-type formulation of bounded integer programs: an alternative approach Naval Res. Logist. Quart., 19 (1972), pp. 699–708 Copyright © 1998 Published by Elsevier B.V.